<BlogPost
	title="July 4th at Old Orchard Beach: What to Expect"
	description="Fireworks over the Atlantic, a packed boardwalk, and the best lobster roll you'll have all summer. Here's how to do July 4th at Old Orchard Beach right."
	date="April 2026"
	category="Seasonal Guide"
	slug="july-4th-old-orchard-beach"
>
	<p>July 4th is the single biggest day of the summer at Old Orchard Beach. The beach fills by noon, Old Orchard Street becomes a river of people by evening, fireworks launch over the Atlantic at 9:45 PM, and the entire town hums with a chaotic, festive energy that's hard to find anywhere else in New England. Here's how it works — and how to enjoy it without spending four hours in traffic or circling for parking.</p>

	<h2>The Fireworks</h2>

	<p>Fireworks are launched from the beach between the Pier and Palace Playland at approximately <strong>9:45–10:00 PM</strong>. These are full professional fireworks shows — the same setup that runs every Thursday night throughout the summer, scaled up for the holiday.</p>

	<p><strong>Best viewing spots:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Anywhere on the main beach near the pier — arrive by 7–8 PM at the latest to stake out space on the sand</li>
		<li>The pier itself (get there well before dark — it gets crowded early)</li>
		<li>Joseph's By the Sea rooftop — if you're booking a dinner, this is the move</li>
		<li>Walking north toward Pine Point gets progressively quieter and less crowded</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>2026 note:</strong> July 4 falls on a Saturday. The weekly Thursday night fireworks land on <strong>July 2</strong> — so guests arriving mid-week get a fireworks doubleheader before the main event on the 4th.</p>

	<h2>Pre-Fireworks: July 4th Events</h2>

	<p><strong>Ocean Park Parade — 10:00 AM</strong><br />
	The Independence Day Parade kicks off at 10 AM on Temple Ave. at the Bell Tower in Ocean Park, the Victorian community adjacent to OOB. Led by the Ocean Park Band and a color guard, it's short and old-fashioned in the best way.</p>

	<p><strong>Sand Sculpture Contest — July 3</strong><br />
	Typically held the day before the 4th — a family-friendly competition on the beach.</p>

	<p><strong>195th Army National Guard Band — 7:00 PM</strong><br />
	A free patriotic concert at the Seaside Pavilion (8 Sixth St.) beginning at 7 PM on July 4. A good way to spend the evening hours before fireworks without fighting for a beach spot early.</p>

	<h2>Palace Playland on July 4th</h2>

	<p>The park opens at <strong>noon on weekends</strong> and stays open well into the evening — typically until 10 PM or later on July 4 weekend. The park sits directly adjacent to the fireworks launch zone, so guests inside can watch from the grounds.</p>

	<p>Lines on July 4th weekend are the longest of the year. <strong>Ride early (noon–4 PM)</strong> if you're going — by 5 PM the park is packed. The Ferris Wheel at sunset is worth the wait.</p>

	<h2>Food and Dining</h2>

	<p>Every food spot on the strip will have lines from roughly 5–9 PM. Two strategies work: eat a late lunch (2–4 PM) or an early dinner (4:30–5:30 PM) before the evening crowds arrive.</p>

	<p><strong>The classics:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Pier French Fries</strong> — The mandatory OOB food stop, open since 1932. Thick-cut fries, fried dough, hot dogs. Located right at the base of the pier.</li>
		<li><strong>Bill's Pizza</strong> — A pier institution since 1949. Hand-made dough on site.</li>
		<li><strong>JJ's Eatery</strong> — The best breakfast in OOB for an early morning arrival on the 4th.</li>
		<li><strong>Johnny Shucks Maine Lobster</strong> — Lobster rolls, well-reviewed for freshness. Worth the wait.</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>For dinner with a view:</strong> <strong>Joseph's By the Sea</strong> is the fine dining standard-bearer in OOB — rooftop and dining room ocean views, open for 50+ years. Book a reservation for July 4th dinner weeks in advance. The rooftop is the best seat in town for the fireworks.</p>

	<h2>Crowds and Logistics</h2>

	<p>July 4th weekend generates over a million Maine Turnpike transactions. Expect serious traffic on I-95 northbound from late morning through early evening. Old Orchard Street itself may be closed to vehicles as a safety measure — the town has done this in recent years. Approach from the north (Saco side) or use the western municipal lots.</p>

	<p>ATM fees downtown are notoriously high on holiday weekends. Bring cash in advance.</p>

	<h2>Parking on July 4th</h2>

	<p>This is the hardest parking day of the year. Here's the honest breakdown:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Arrive before noon</strong> to get a convenient municipal lot ($3/hour, meters active through Labor Day)</li>
		<li>After 2 PM, plan to park in residential side streets 10–15 minutes from the beach</li>
		<li>The <strong>Milliken Street area</strong> is the local tip — steps from the beach, typically less jammed than the main lots</li>
		<li>Private lots near the pier charge $20–40 on peak days</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>The Case for Staying in Saco</h2>

	<p>Saco Bay Hotel is less than two miles from Old Orchard Beach — a five-minute drive, or bikeable via the Eastern Trail. On July 4th, this proximity makes the entire day easier: drive in early, park before the crowds, return to the hotel to change and rest, and head back for the evening. You're not stuck in resort-town traffic trying to get in or out.</p>

	<p>From Saco, you can also add a morning at Funtown Splashtown USA before the afternoon beach crowd builds — the park is roughly 1.5 miles from Saco Bay Hotel and typically less chaotic than OOB on the 4th.</p>

	<h2>Beach Conditions</h2>

	<p>Early July averages: air temperature 76–78°F, water temperature roughly 58–63°F — cold by most standards, but people swim. July is OOB's driest month (about 3 inches of rain for the entire month). Evening temperatures drop to the low-to-mid 60s after dark. Bring a layer for the fireworks.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>The One Tip That Changes July 4th</strong>
		<p>If you're coming from Saco Bay Hotel, drive in by 9 AM on July 4th. Park, walk to the beach, enjoy a quiet morning before the crowds arrive, grab breakfast at JJ's, and you'll already have your spot staked out before the afternoon rush hits. By the time the parking lots are full, you'll be settled on the sand with nowhere you need to be.</p>
	</div>
